        <div class="project-badge">Government Intelligence</div>
    </div>
    <p class="project-description">
        <strong>The Challenge:</strong> State and local governments are drowning in feedback‚Äîconstituent emails, town hall comments, employee surveys, service complaints, social media mentions‚Äîbut it's scattered across channels, trapped in silos, and analyzed too slowly to matter. The real challenge isn't collecting more voices; it's making sense of what people are actually saying across contexts before the next crisis hits or the budget cycle closes.
    </p>
    <div class="project-highlights">
        <h5>How Qualtrics Enables This:</h5>
        <ul>
            <li>Cross-channel text analytics that unify feedback from surveys, emails, public comments, and open-ended responses into coherent intelligence</li>
            <li>Contextual sentiment analysis revealing not just "are people upset" but "about what specifically, in which communities, and why now"</li>
            <li>Role-based dashboards delivering constituent sentiment to elected officials, operational metrics to department heads, and service quality trends to frontline managers</li>
            <li>Real-time alerting when sentiment shifts dramatically‚Äîcatching emerging issues before they explode into public relations disasters</li>
            <li>Trend analysis showing whether policy changes, communications, or service improvements actually moved the needle on public perception</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="project-impact">
        <div class="impact-metric">
            <span class="impact-icon">üéØ</span>
            <span><strong>What Success Looks Like:</strong> Early warning systems that prevent crises, resource allocation decisions informed by what communities actually need (not just what's loudest), elected officials equipped with real constituent intelligence during budget debates, and proof that responsive government actually changes public sentiment.</span>
        </div>
